<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   MITI Official Views 
Macroeconomic Measures </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1203050794 Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN in Japanese 11 Mar 94 
Morning Edition p 11 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1203050794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo ASAHI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] On 10 March, a top official at the Ministry of 
International Trade and Industry commented on a package of 
external economic measures which the government plans to compile 
in two stages -- in late March, and before the July summit 
meeting of the major industrialized nations. The official 
stated: "Macroeconomic measures should be included in a 
market-opening package to be compiled in late March." He 
stressed that the ruling coalition parties need to make a quick 
decision on the tax system reform which is currently under 
discussion. 
  With regard to macroeconomic measures, the idea of 
increasing 
the amount of public works spending has now cropped up. 
However, a U.S. Government official previously said: "Even if 
the public works program is revised, the U.S. Government will 
not highly appreciate it." It appears that this U.S. view has 
been conveyed to the Japanese Government. For this reason, the 
major point at issue is how the government will spell out its 
direction in tax system reform. 
  Referring to the possibility of Japan offering to implement 
[income] tax reductions of 6 trillion yen a year for three 
consecutive years without deciding on revenue sources to fill in 
shortfalls therefrom, the senior official insisted the revenue 
source question should be decided at the same time, saying: 
"Otherwise, that is tantamount to announcing a plan to issue 
18-trillion-yen worth of deficit-covering public bonds." He 
then added, "Chief Cabinet Secretary Masayoshi Takemura who is 
in charge of finalizing the package, and the Social Democratic 
Party of Japan should come up with responsible proposals on 
this," thus serving warning to the two who are reluctant about 
resolving the two issues at the same time. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

