<F P=100> ANNEX </F>
<F P=101> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yi Yong-tok on Early N-S Exchange of Envoys </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1503053494 Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database in Japanese 15 
Mar 94 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1503053494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo Nikkei Telecom Database </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Tadao Karino and Masaharu Shimokawa; from MAINICHI </F>
SHIMBUN 15 March Morning Edition] 
  [Text] Seoul, 14 Mar -- Yi Yong-tok, South Korean deputy 
prime minister and minister of national unification, gave an 
exclusive interview to MAINICHI SHIMBUN on 14 March. On the 
unresolved issue of an exchange of special envoys between North 
and South Korea, Yi said: "Theoretically, it is still possible 
to have the exchange in time," but "that is only what we are 
hoping for. In reality, this will be difficult to achieve." 
  He indicated he was pessimistic about the possibility of 
exchanging special envoys before 21 March, when the third round 
of high level talks between the United States and the DPRK 
(North Korea) is scheduled to be held. 
  Yi revealed that during recent talks with visiting U.S. 
Assistant Secretary of State Robert Gallucci, they had agreed 
that "if the exchange of special envoys does not materialize, 
the third round of U.S.-DPRK talks will be postponed," 
indicating the possibility the talks may be delayed. 
  Yi cited the fact that on 12 March North Korea virtually 
withdrew the four prerequisites it had set [for the exchange of 
envoys] -- including "discontinuation of military exercises 
using nuclear arms" -- at the North-South working level 
negotiations in Panmunjom, and predicted that "even if the 
exchange of special envoys could not take place in time, I am 
optimistic that we will be able to reach agreement (in the end)." 
  However, as far as the timetable for exchanging envoys is 
concerned, Yi said: "We would not be able to tell before the 
working level meeting on 16 March." 
  Yi stated that the exchange of special envoys with North 
Korea has already been agreed between the North and South, and 
it would amount to an indirect dialogue between the leaders of 
the two sides, which might open the way to direct dialogue. 
Seoul, therefore, intends to work for this patiently. 
  He also said that the reason the North is not eager to 
exchange envoys "seems to be that it wants to give priority to 
negotiations with the United States. However, the North is 
surely aware of the importance of direct North-South dialogue." 
  Touching on the nuclear inspections currently being 
conducted 
by the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA), Yi said: 
"While we cannot say they are proceeding smoothly, they are 
somehow progressing." 
  On recent developments in North Korea, Yi said: "There are 
signs of policy change, such as the North's admitting the 
failure of its economic construction. It also seems to be in 
the process of reconsidering its withdrawal from the nuclear 
Nonproliferation Treaty (NPT)." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

