<H3> <TI>   Group Proposes N-S Body To Monitor ROK Dumping </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1403112794 Pyongyang KCNA in English 1037 GMT 14 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1403112794 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Pyongyang, March 14 (KCNA) -- The Korean Anti-Nuke 
Peace Committee and the Central Committee of the Korean 
Environmental Conservation Union proposed that the anti-nuke, 
environmental organisations of the North and the South conduct 
joint survey and monitoring activities at an early date to probe 
the very truth behind the nuclear waste dumping by the South 
Korean authorities and check it. 
  This proposal was made in a letter sent today to the 
Alliance 
of the Anti-Nuke Peace Movement, the Alliance of the 
Environmental Movement and the Civic Federation for Economic 
Justice of South Korea. 
  Noting that the South Korean authorities had dumped 11,000 
trillion becquerels of nuclear waste into the sea in the 1986-92 
period, the letter goes on: 
  "Such nuclear waste dumping by the South Korean authorities 
is a crude breach of the international conventions on protection 
and conservation of the sea environment and an anti-national, 
anti-human crime inflicting immeasurable disasters on our nation 
and mankind. 
  "The random dumping of nuclear waste by South Korea vividly 
shows how far the South Korean authorities have gone in 
developing nuclear arms while crying over `suspected nuclear 
programme of the North.' 
  "It is entirely natural that in South Korea environmental 
organisations, people and broad public circles took issue with 
the authorities' criminal dumping of nuclear waste and have 
risen in a struggle against it. 
  "We hope your organisations will turn out more courageously 
in the just struggle in the future to check the South Korean 
authorities' criminal nuclear waste dumping and nuclear arms 
development." 

</TEXT>

