<F P=100> North Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Daily Warns Japan To `Act Prudently'; Cites Hata </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1503044694 Pyongyang KCNA in English 0430 GMT 15 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1503044694 </F>
<F P=104>  Pyongyang KCNA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Japan Warned Not To Impede Denuclearization of Korean </F>
Peninsula" -- KCNA headline] 
  [Text] Pyongyang, March 15 (KCNA) -- MINJU CHOSON today 
warns that the Japanese authorities must act prudently, mindful 
that their ill-intentioned words and deeds might cause 
unpredictable grave consequences. 
  The news analyst says: 
  Recently the Japanese Foreign Minister, Tsutomu Hata raved 
that if the DPRK "refuses again to accept inspection or takes an 
irresolute attitude," Japan would "sternly counter it," alleging 
that the DPRK "is going to make nuclear weapons" and "is 
suspected of having one or two nuclear bombs." 
  His outburst came at a time when the DPRK and the United 
States have agreed on immediate steps of simultaneous action and 
the third round of talks between them is soon to be held. This 
shows the Japanese reactionaries intend to attain at any cost 
their sinister purpose of accelerating their nuclear armament on 
the pretext of the "nuclear issue" of the DPRK. 
  Japan's nuclear armament and overseas aggrandizement have 
reached a serious danger line. 
  Japan has stockpiled a colossal amount of nuclear material 
and laid a material and technical foundation for the manufacture 
of nuclear weapons. 
  With Japan's nuclear armament presenting a nuclear threat in 
actuality, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula cannot 
be realised, and even if it is realised, it cannot ensure peace 
and security in this part of the world. 
  Judging from facts, we conclude that however hard we may 
strive to denuclearize the Korean peninsula, it cannot be 
realised and, accordingly, the inter-Korean joint declaration on 
denuclearization might be reduced to a mere sheet of paper. 
  Then we will have to reconsider our position toward the 
denuclearization of the Korean peninsula and the inter-Korean 
joint declaration will have to be nullified. 
  In case the Japanese authorities' rash remarks worsen the 
problem, Japan will be wholly to blame for it. 
  The Japanese authorities will have to account for their each 
word and deed and dearly pay for it. 

</TEXT>

