<F P=100> Laos </F>
<H3> <TI>   Press Release Issued on Chea Sim Visit </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK1503100994 Vientiane PASASON in Lao 8 Mar 94 pp 1, 3 </F>
<F P=103> BK1503100994 </F>
<F P=104>  Vientiane PASASON </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Lao </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["Press Release" on the 5 to 7 March visit to the Lao </F>
People's Democratic Republic by a high-level delegation of the 
National Assembly of the Kingdom of Cambodia headed by Chairman 
Samdech Chea Sim -- dated 7 March] 
  [Text] At the invitation of His Excellency [H.E.] Saman 
Vi-gnaket, chairman of the Lao People's Democratic Republic 
[LPDR] National Assembly, H.E. Chea Sim, chairman of the Kingdom 
of Cambodia [KC] National Assembly, led a high-level KC National 
Assembly delegation on an official friendship visit to the LPDR 
from 5 to 7 March 1994. 
  During their visit, Samdech Chea Sim and delegation paid 
separate courtesy calls on H.E. Nouhak Phoumsavan and H.E. 
Khamtai Siphandon, respectively president and prime minister of 
the LPDR. 
  During the courtesy calls, H.E. Nouhak Phoumsavan stressed 
that Lao-Cambodian ties consist of fine relations of friendship, 
fraternal solidarity, neighborliness, and comradeship. The 
traditional fine relations and cooperation between the two 
countries have existed since ancient times. The peoples of the 
two countries have practiced similar customs and traditions, 
ardently given support and assistance to each other, and shared 
weal and woe both during the periods of struggle against 
colonialism and neocolonialism and of national defense and 
national construction in each country. H.E. Khamtai Siphandon 
regarded that in the new period, there is a need to further 
strengthen the long-standing traditional relations of 
friendship, solidarity, and multifaceted cooperation between the 
LPDR and the KC in coordinating with each other to improve and 
readjust the forms and methods of cooperation for better harmony 
and higher efficiency for the immediate and long- term common 
and individual interests. This will ardently conform to the 
ever-increasing strong aspirations of the peoples of Laos and 
Cambodia in building their respective countries with peace, 
national independence, and prosperity. 
  The receptions and conversations between the hosts and 
guests 
were permeated with an atmosphere of profound friendship from 
beginning to end. 
  Samdech Chea Sim and delegation laid a wreath at the 
Monument 
of Unknown Combatants and visited many places of economic and 
cultural significance in Vientiane capital and Vientiane 
Province. Wherever Samdech Chea Sim and delegation visited, 
they were given a warm and intimate welcome by the local 
administrations, authorities, and Lao residents. 
  A meeting between the KC National Assembly delegation headed 
by Samdech Chea Sim and the LPDR National Assembly delegation 
headed by H.E. Saman Vi-gnaket to exchange views on the 
situation took place at the Lao National Assembly in Vientiane 
capital in an atmosphere of friendship, sincerity, and mutual 
understanding. At the meeting, the two sides informed each 
other of outstanding situations in their respective countries 
and exchanged views on the strengthening of relations and 
cooperation between the two countries and between the two 
legislative organizations. They exchanged views on regional and 
international issues of mutual interest. The Lao side regarded 
that the official friendship visit by Samdech Chea Sim and 
delegation constituted a gesture of historic significance, 
contributing to strengthening and multiplying the intimate, 
normal relations which have existed since ancient times between 
Laos and Cambodia. At the same time, it also wholeheartedly 
hailed the increasing achievements of the implementation of the 
Paris agreement, which is the process of achieving peace and 
national reconciliation in Cambodia; as well as the successful 
National Assembly elections; the endorsement and promulgation of 
the new Constitution; the revival of the constitutional 
monarchy; the return to the throne of the Kingdom of Cambodia by 
Samdech Norodom Sihanouk who has played the supreme, historical 
role in realizing the unification, peace, political stability, 
national reconciliation, rehabilitation, and reconstruction; and 
the establishment of the Government of the KC. 
  The Lao side highly assessed the role of the KC National 
Assembly in the process of national reconciliation and in 
developing and building the KC into an independent, peaceful, 
neutral, nonaligned, and prosperous country. 
  Samdech Chea Sim and delegation hailed the great 
achievements in various fields made by the Lao Government and 
people, noting that such successes have been scored thanks to 
the policy of principled and all-around restructuring under the 
clear- and far-sighted leadership of the Lao People's 
Revolutionary Party. He also hailed the role of the LPDR NA in 
building and broadening the popular democratic regime, carrying 
out socioeconomic development, and pursuing the broad foreign 
policy of peace, independence, friendship, and cooperation, 
thereby ardently contributing to turning Laos into a country of 
peace, independence, democracy, unification, and prosperity. 
  The two sides expressed satisfaction with the traditional 
fine relations of friendship which have continued for centuries 
and have thus been worthy of being good-neighborly countries 
which have practiced cooperation in many fields. They see a 
need to incessantly multiply and increase such relations and 
cooperation on the basis of the principles of respect for each 
other's independence, sovereignty, and territorial integrity; 
noninterference in each other's internal affairs; refraining 
from the use force and coercion; resolving all problems between 
the two countries peacefully; cooperation; equality; and mutual 
benefits. They regarded the exchange of visits of the high-level 
delegations headed by the prime ministers of the two countries; 
the Laos- Cambodia joint statement issued in July 1993; and the 
Laos-Cambodia joint declaration and the agreement on economic, 
scientific, technical, and cultural cooperation between the two 
countries signed by the two governments in Phnom Penh in 
November 1993 as very significant to the relations and 
cooperation between Laos and Cambodia in the new period. 
  The two sides were unanimous in planning to set up a 
friendship association between the LPDR National Assembly and 
the KC National Assembly to exchange delegations at various 
levels, and to assist each other in the sphere of legislative 
work on a regular basis. 
  The two sides share a common aim of establishing close 
relations and cooperation with the legislative institutions of 
other countries in the region and the Interparliamentary Union 
to contribute to turning Southeast Asia into a region of peace, 
friendship, and cooperation. 
  The Lao side expressed extreme appreciation with the success 
of the visit to the LPDR this time by Samdech Chea Sim and 
delegation, terming it a new glorious milestone in the history 
of relations between the two legislative institutions as well as 
the two countries. 
  Samdech Chea Sim and delegation highly valued the success of 
the visit and expressed profound thanks to the Lao National 
Assembly and people for having accorded an intimate welcome 
filled with a spirit of fraternal warmth and good neighborliness 
to the KC National Assembly delegation during its official 
friendship visit to the LPDR. On behalf of the KC National 
Assembly, Chairman Samdech Chea Sim extended an invitation to 
H.E. Saman Vi-gnaket, chairman of the LPDR National Assembly, 
and delegation to pay an official friendship visit to the KC. 
The chairman expressed his thanks to Samdech Chea Sim and 
accepted the invitation with pleasure. The time and date of the 
visit will be notified to the Cambodian side through diplomatic 
channels. 
  [Dated] Vientiane, 7 March 1994 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

