<F P=100> Thailand </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cambodian `Bandits' Abduct, Release Officials </TI></H3>
<H4>   Four Abducted 13 Mar </H4>
<F P=102> BK1403035494 Bangkok BANGKOK POST in English 14 Mar 94 p 8 </F>
<F P=103> BK1403035494 </F>
<F P=104>  Bangkok BANGKOK POST </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Four officials working for a Royally-sponsored 
project in Ta Phraya District were abducted by Cambodian bandits 
yesterday. The 13 bandits, armed with rocket-propelled grenade 
launchers and assault rifles, slipped across the Thai-Cambodian 
border into Site Two. The former camp in Ban Thap Thai, Tambon 
Thap Sadet has been transformed into a land development project 
for border inhabitants under the Thapthim Siam 03 project 
sponsored by HRH [Her Royal Highness] Princess Chulaphon. 
  The bandits forced Mr Cha-on Thongtonhak and Mr Phadung 
Wongsapan, two officials of the land development unit of the 
Land Department, and two temporary employees, Mr Charat Phutson 
and Mr Nak Khathong, into Cambodia's Ampil village, in Banteay 
Meanchey Province. About two hours after the abduction, the 
bandits freed Mr Nak and told him to fetch 120,000 baht ransom 
in exchange for the release of his three colleagues today at 3 
p.m. at a rendezvous point to be determined later. The bandits 
would notify him later about the location for the rendezvous, 
Nak told police. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-6158 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas050_m_94007" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-EAS-94-050 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  15 Mar 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> Thailand </F>
<H3> <TI>   Cambodian `Bandits' Abduct, Release Officials </TI></H3>
<H4>   Minister Views `Strong Measures' </H4>
<F P=102> BK1503092394 Bangkok Radio Thailand Network in Thai 0530 GMT 
15 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1503092394 </F>
<F P=104>  Bangkok Radio Thailand Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Thai </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Defense Minister General Wichit Sukmak talked to 
reporters this morning at Government House about the problem of 
robberies by Cambodian soldiers. 
  He said that he agrees with the Army commander about 
implementing strong measures against the Cambodian robbers. 
Regarding preventive measures, all sides must coordinate with 
each other to make them work. These include those in the 
government administrative circle -- the Interior Ministry and 
the unit in charge of national security; and the military with 
the major tasks of preventing violations of sovereignty -- the 
Royal Thai Army and the Royal Thai Navy. In the case of serious 
incidents, the Royal Thai Air Force should also lend a hand. 
  In any case, the defense minister agrees with the idea of 
implementing extremely decisive actions against the bandits in 
the future. The reason is that many Thais have been killed and 
wounded. At the same time coordination has begun with the 
National Defense Ministry of Cambodia and the Cambodian side 
pledged to try to prevent such incidents from occurring. 
  Meanwhile, a group of armed Cambodian bandits held three 
Thai 
officials of the Thapthim Sayam project and demanded ransom. 
Following coordination between Thai authorities and Cambodian 
representatives, the Thai side agreed to pay 120,000 baht in 
exchange for the release of the hostages. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

