<H3> <TI>   Military Budget for Bougainville Increased </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK1303125894 Melbourne Radio Australia in English 1100 GMT 
13 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1303125894 </F>
<F P=104>  Melbourne Radio Australia </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Papua New Guinea's [PNG] prime minister, Paias 
Wingti, has announced more money for military operations against 
secessionist rebels on the island of Bougainville. The 
announcement comes just days after the United Nations Human 
Rights Commission adopted, by consensus, a resolution relating 
to the conflict on Bougainville. The resolution called on the 
PNG Government to invite UN investigators to visit Bougainville 
to look into human rights abuses. Sean Dorney reports: 
  [Begin recording] [Dorney] Reviewing a trooping of the 
colors ceremony at (Torano) Bay, just outside Port Moresby, at 
the weekend, Prime Minister Paias Wingti praised the 1st 
Battalion of the Pacific island's regiment, claiming that its 
ability to win the hearts and minds of the people have led to 
abiding their operation gaining public confidence and respect. 
And Mr. Wingti announced there'd be more money for the army. 
  [Wingti] Yesterday, the cabinet also made a very important 
decision to allocate 5 million kina, new money for the 
operations on Bougainville for the defense force. 
  [Dorney] The 1st Battalion has had 21 soldiers killed in the 
Bougainville conflict. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

