<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   IAEA Inspectors Finish Inspection, Depart </TI></H3>
<H4>   Team Departs Pyongyang 15 Mar </H4>
<F P=102> SK1503024294 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 0200 GMT 15 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK1503024294 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Korean </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Cha Man-sun from Vienna] </F>
  [Text] The International Atomic Energy Agency [IAEA] 
inspection team departed Pyongyang at 1000 [0100 GMT] on 15 
March by air after completing its 12-day inspection of North 
Korean nuclear facilities. 
  The IAEA inspection team was scheduled to stay one day in 
Beijing; however, it will proceed directly to IAEA headquarters 
in Vienna. 
  Mr. Kyd, IAEA information director, revealed that the 
inspection team was to stay one day in Beijing, but the team 
will arrive in Vienna on 16 March after changing its original 
plan in response to an emergency directive from the IAEA 
Secretariat. 
  The IAEA will decide if it will convene a special Board of 
Governors meeting this weekend after hearing the inspection 
team's report on detailed results of the inspection activities. 
  The major board members stated that the inspection for 
examination of conversion of nuclear materials was insufficient, 
including difficulties the team experienced in extracting test 
material of nuclear materials due to North Korea's lack of 
cooperation. As a result, it seems that convocation of a 
special Board of Governors meeting next week is inevitable. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

