<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   IAEA Inspectors Finish Inspection, Depart </TI></H3>
<H4>   Arrives in Beijing </H4>
<F P=102> OW1503062394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0556 GMT 15 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1503062394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Beijing, March 15 KYODO -- A weary-looking team 
of inspectors from the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) 
arrived in Beijing on Tuesday [15 March] from Pyongyang after a 
two-week tour inspecting North Korea's nuclear facilities. 
  Team leader Olli Heinonen refused to comment on how the 
inspections went or to answer questions concerning rumors that 
the North Korean Government denied the team access to some of 
the seven agreed-upon nuclear sites. 
  "We don't give any statements. That will be done in Vienna 
tonight," Heinonen said. "We had a nice pleasant trip. We all 
want to go home now." 
  Upon arrival, the team immediately booked tickets out of 
Beijing, with five members scheduled to arrive in Zurich later 
Tuesday. 
  The IAEA will release a statement in Vienna concerning the 
trip later Tuesday, Heinonen said. 
  Prior to this round of inspections, North Korea had delayed 
for more than a year IAEA inspections of its nuclear program, 
fueling accusations that it was trying to develop nuclear 
weapons. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

