<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Efforts Toward N-S Envoy Exchange </TI></H3>
<H4>   NUB Minister Cited </H4>
<F P=102> SK1503021094 Seoul YONHAP in English 0159 GMT 15 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1503021094 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 15 (YONHAP) -- Yi Yong-tok, South 
Korean deputy prime minister and minister of the National 
Unification Board (NUB), said on Tuesday that South and North 
Korea would not be able to exchange special envoys by March 21, 
the scheduled date for Pyongyang-Washington talks. 
  Lee, in an interview with the Japanese daily MAINICHI 
SHIMBUN, said, "theoretically, realization of the special envoy 
exchange is possible before March 21, but it is nothing more 
than our (South Korea's) wishful thinking. Actually, we have 
little time. It is difficult." 
  Yi added that since Washington agreed with Seoul not to hold 
the talks unless the special envoy exchange is realized, the 
scheduled third round of high-level talks between Pyongyang and 
Washington seems impossible either. 
  In one promising development, North Korea virtually withdrew 
four preconditions for the envoy exchange including "suspension 
of the nuclear military exercise" at an inter-Korean 
working-level contact last Saturday. 
  "With North Korea's change of attitude, although the special 
envoys may not be exchanged before March 21, a final agreement 
on the exchange may be reached by that date," he said. 
  South Korea will press the envoy exchange because it is part 
of preparatory work for an inter-Korean summit meeting, Yi 
emphasized. 
  Yi said North Korea had admitted its economic failure, 
adding 
that Pyongyang seemed to be re-evaluating its announced 
withdrawal from the nuclear nonproliferation treaty (NPT). 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

