<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Efforts Toward N-S Envoy Exchange </TI></H3>
<H4>   Minister on Progress Toward Exchange </H4>
<F P=102> SK1503082594 Seoul YONHAP in English 0813 GMT 15 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1503082594 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 15 (YONHAP) -- Yi Yong-tok, deputy 
prime minister and minister of the National Unification Board 
(NUB), said Tuesday that Pyongyang-Washington relations will 
hardly advance unless inter-Korean ties are placed on the right 
track. 
  Yi told reporters that progress in inter-Korean relations 
will help improve the North's links with Japan and the United 
States, emphasizing that an envoy exchange is a precondition for 
the third round of Pyongyang-Washington high-level talks. 
  South and North Korea have held three working-level contacts 
on exchanging special envoys since the North agreed to accept 
nuclear inspections by the International Atomic Energy Agency 
(IAEA) late last month, but failed to narrow their differences 
on the envoys' mission and how to conduct the exchange. 
  Yi said, "We are accepting most of the North Korean demands 
on procedure. But some of the seven items North Korea proposed 
under the envoys' mission have been analyzed as related to 
Pyongyang's same old strategy toward Seoul." 
  For example, Pyongyang presented "the problem of forging a 
great unity among all the people" as one facet of the mission, 
which the South says is related to the old "unification front" 
stategy. 
  Yi said, "The special envoy exchange is significant in 
solving the North Korean nuclear problem and breaking the 
deadlock in inter- Korean relations. Anyway, I think Pyongyang 
also intends to exchange envoys." 

</TEXT>

