<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Efforts Toward N-S Envoy Exchange </TI></H3>
<H4>   Team Spirit Set as Condition </H4>
<F P=102> SK1503083294 Seoul YONHAP in English 0803 GMT 15 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1503083294 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 15 (YONHAP) -- South Korea and the 
United States on Tuesday reaffirmed that they will hold the 
joint military exercise "Team Spirit" this year if IAEA 
inspections of North Korean nuclear facilities are deemed 
unsatisfactory and an inter-Korean envoy exchange fails to take 
place. 
  The reaffirmation came at a meeting between South Korean 
Defense Minister Yi Pyong-tae and U.S. Deputy Secretary of 
Defense Frank Wisner in Seoul on Tuesday. 
  The two officials also discussed security on the Korean 
peninsula and strengthening bilateral security cooperation, 
officials said. 
  Wisner told Yi that the Korean peninsula is vital to U.S. 
strategy while the two officials agreed that the security 
arrangement between the United States and South Korea remains 
firm, the officials said. 
  The meeting was attended by other military officials from 
both sides. 
  Wisner, visiting South Korea for the first time, is 
scheduled 
to visit the U.S. Second Infantry Division, an underground 
tunnel dug by North Koreans in the Demilitarized Zone, South 
Korea's First Infantry Divison and the Joint Security Area of 
the truce village of Panmunjom before departing on Thursday. 

</TEXT>

