<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   DPRK Party Official's SRV, Laos Visits Noted </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1503055494 Seoul YONHAP in English 0545 GMT 15 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1503055494 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 15 (YONHAP) -- North Korea may make 
important decisions on its nuclear program and relations with 
the United States at the seventh meeting of the Ninth Supreme 
People's Assembly slated for early April, officials here said on 
Tuesday. 
  Hwang Chang-yop, North Korean Workers' Party secretary in 
charge of international affairs, visited Vietnam from March 7-10 
to find out how Hanoi improved relations with Washington in 
resuming economic cooperation. 
  Vietnam's example in enhancing relations with the United 
States may have served as a valuable case study for North Korea, 
an official at the National Unification Board (NUB) said. 
  Hwang met with senior officials from the Vietnamese 
Communist 
Party to discuss the issue of returning the remains of U.S. 
soldiers killed during the Korean war (1950-53). 
  After visiting Vietnam, Hwang stopped over in Laos on March 
11 to negotiate North Korean purchases of Laotian rice. 
  The NUB official said, "we are taking note that Hwang, who 
is 
a mastermind of North Korean diplomacy, visited these countries 
shortly before the meeting of the Supreme People's Assembly is 
to be held." 
  The Assembly usually meets to deal with party reorganization 
and the budget and to make decisions on important matters. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-6194 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas050_d_94017" </HT>


<HEADER>
