<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ambassador to U.S. Calls for More Investment </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1503021794 Seoul YONHAP in English 0139 GMT 15 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1503021794 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] New York, March 14 (YONHAP) -- South Korean 
Ambassador Han Sung-su has called on U.S. companies to increase 
investment in South Korea, saying his country is providing new 
opportunities for foreign entrepreneurs. 
  In a letter to the editor of the WALL STREET JOURNAL printed 
in its Monday issue, he noted that the South Korean Government 
is tearing down virtually all trade barriers against foreign 
firms making inroads into the country, particularly those 
against foreign direct and equity investment. 
  Refuting a story published by the influential economic 
newspaper on Feb. 25 that South Korea is the least attractive 
market for foreign investors in East Asia, Han said South Korea 
offers a number of attractions for American investors. 
  Among them are the 15th largest gross national product in 
the 
world, the 12th largest trading partner of the United States, a 
population of 43 million, a solid foundation for manufacturing, 
an educated and skilled labor force, the country's geographical 
location as a relay point for trade with China, Russia and 
Japan, and political stability for sustained economic growth, he 
enumerated. 
  Because of foreign invasions in the past, Koreans once 
opposed foreign investment: This xenophobia has now changed to 
an understanding that the Korean economy is mutually dependent 
on other countries' economies for sustained growth and that 
foreign investment and technology imports are necessary for 
further development. 
  Han said Koreans are well aware that foreign loans, which 
helped to develop the country's economy, are no longer 
instrumental in importing the technology the economy needs in 
its present stage of growth. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

