<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Lost, Stolen ROK Passports Used by Asians </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1503021594 Seoul THE KOREA HERALD in English 15 Mar 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> SK1503021594 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul THE KOREA HERALD </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Security authorities are sounding the alarm as lost 
and stolen South Korean passports are being abused by other 
Asian nationals, who use them to enter the United States, Japan 
and other countries. 
  Two Chinese nationals were caught last Dec. 21 trying to 
enter Los Angeles with altered South Korean passports, followed 
by one in New York and another in Chicago Dec. 29, Foreign 
Ministry officials and travel agencies said yesterday. 
  Cambodians, Thais and Turks have been caught using South 
Korean passports in Japan and the United States. 
  Cambodian nationals turned up with four South Korean 
passports Jan. 8 that were stolen separately in Hong Kong, New 
York and Seoul, with the latest incidents occurring in Thailand, 
Belgium, the Philippines and the United States throughout 
January until Feb. 4. 
  Officials said they believe the passports are being sold on 
the black market for $1,500 to $2,000 in places like Bangkok and 
Manila. 
  The concern in Seoul is that due to the rise in illegitimate 
passports, foreign immigration officials may decide to step up 
security checks and entry procedures for South Korean passport 
holders, the officials said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

