<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Unification-Related Ministers Meeting Noted </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1503051894 Seoul YONHAP in English 0510 GMT 15 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1503051894 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 15 (YONHAP) -- The government held a 
unification-related ministers' meeting on Tuesday morning to 
discuss the seventh inter-Korean working-level contact slated 
for Wednesday. 
  At the meeting presided over by Yi Yong-tok, deputy prime 
minister and minister of the National Unification Board (NUB), 
the ministers agreed to strive for an agreement on exchanging 
special envoys at the seventh contact. 
  They also decided to keep pushing for the exchange by March 
21 after analyzing the results of the six inter-Korean 
working-level contacts held so far. 
  The ministers, however, reaffirmed that if North Korea 
delays 
the envoy exchange to the last minute, the third round of 
high-level talks between Pyongyang and Washington should be put 
off too, informed sources said. 
  Meanwhile, Foreign Minister Han Sung-chu reported on the 
results of the International Atomic Energy Agency (IAEA) 
inspection of North Korean nuclear sites, officials said. 
  Defense Minister Yi Pyong-tae and Senior Presidential 
Secretary for Foreign and National Security Affairs Chong 
Chong-uk also attended the meeting. 

</TEXT>

