<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kim Yong-sam on Need for Strong Police Force </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1403114794 Seoul YONHAP in English 0624 GMT 14 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1403114794 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 14 (YONHAP)--President Kim Yong-sam has 
called for a powerful police force, declaring, "We can't 
increase national competitiveness insofar as violence and crime 
are rampant in our society." 
  Speaking on Monday [14 March] at the Korean Police Academy's 
commencement ceremony in Yongin, about 40 kilometers East of 
Seoul, the chief executive said the more advanced a country, the 
more powerful its police. "Rule by law can be realized with a 
strong police force... We can't maintain law and order with a 
weak police force," he stressed. 
  Unlawful, violent demonstrations cannot be justifed under 
any 
circumstances, nor can any violations of law and order be 
forgiven, he added. 
  "The people want the police to be a strong sentry of law and 
order... The police must have a sense of mission to protect the 
people and the nation," he said. 
  Kim said the government would not spare any efforts to 
modernize the country's police force and to improve their 
treatment and working conditions. 

</TEXT>

