<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   ROK To Revise International Trade Related Laws </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1503021394 Seoul THE KOREA HERALD in English 15 Mar 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> SK1503021394 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul THE KOREA HERALD </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The government plans to legislate, revise or abolish 
149 laws this year in a bid to make the legal system of Korea 
fit the emerging international economic order after the 
conclusion of the Uruguay Round multilateral trade negotiations. 
  Thirty-two laws are related to deregulation in the economic 
field. They include the Foreign Trade Law, the Insurance Law 
and the Law on Farmland Ownership. 
  Legislation Minister Pak Song-kyu reported to the weekly 
cabinet meeting yesterday that the Foreign Trade law will be 
revised to allow people to engage in international trade by 
simply reporting their business to the authorities. 
  Pak said the regulation on financial support for Korean 
businesses which suffer losses because of imported products will 
be also modified. 
  He said his office has already handed in 15 bills to the 
National Assembly for consideration. It will seek the 
Assembly's approval for the other bills at the upcoming special 
or regular sessions. 
  The government will draw up a bill on development of the 
information industry to provide tax benefits to the investors in 
this area. 
  Minister Pak said his office is working to draw up a bill on 
the promotion of people's health with a view to providing 
regular health checks to all people. 
  The bill would form a fund for national health promotion 
using part of the profits from the sale of cigarettes, a 
government monopoly. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

