<H3> <TI>   Changes in Civil Servants' Property To Be Studied </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1503045794 Seoul YONHAP in English 0413 GMT 15 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1503045794 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 15 (YONHAP) -- The administration's 
ethics committee on Tuesday [15 March] started looking into the 
real estate holdings of 680 civil servants ranked at grade one 
and above who reported changes in their property status late 
last month. 
  The investigation is focusing on how their real estate 
holdings have changed since the last property registration early 
last year, committee officials said. 
  To carry out its work, the committee obtained real estate 
registers from the Home and Construction Ministries and the 
National Tax Administration. 
  The committee has also asked banks and other financial 
institutions to provide financial data related to 120 to 130 
civil servants who registered no change in their financial 
assets, though they are considered to have made asset changes. 
  Examination of the financial data will start early next 
month 
when the committee obtains the data, an official said. 
  The investigation will be completed toward the end of May, 
and those civil servants found to have falsely registered 
propertychanges will face punishment including dismissal and 
fines of up to 20 million won. 

</TEXT>

