<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Plans Changed on TGV Technology Transfer </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1203091694 Seoul YONHAP in English 0828 GMT 12 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1203091694 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 12 (YONHAP) -- GEC Alsthom, selected as 
priority negotiator on the supply of trainsets to the projected 
Seoul-Pusan high-speed railway line, has agreed to transfer its 
TGV (Train a Grande Vitesse) technology individually to members 
of the consortium to be formed for the project, instead of 
through any particular member, Daewoo Heavy Industries, Ltd. 
said over the weekend. 
  Late last year, the French company named Hyundai Precision 
&amp; 
Industry Co. as the consortium's prime contractor in order to 
transfer its technology only through Hyundai, but the agreement 
was a reversal of this decision. 
  Under the agreement, GEC Alsthom will transfer its 
technology 
related to the manufacture of TGV locomotives and coaches 
equally to consortium members, the officials said. 
  Daewoo and GEC Alsthom will negotiate details of the 
technology transfer and consortium forming in the near future, 
they added. 
  Because of the agreement between Daewoo and GEC Alsthom, the 
forming of a consortium for the production of high-speed 
trainsets will be expedited, along with the negotiations between 
the government and the French firm for the final contract. 
  Officials of Hyundai Precision &amp; Industry Co. refused to 
make any official comments on the Daewoo-GEC Alsthom agreement 
but unofficially welcomed it, saying it would expedite the 
forming of the consortium. 

</TEXT>

