<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Daewoo Included in Consortium </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1503064894 Seoul YONHAP in English 0602 GMT 15 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1503064894 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 15 (YONHAP) -- GEC Alsthom, the 
Anglo-French company chosen as the priority negotiator for the 
Seoul-Pusan high-speed railway project, announced Tuesday [15 
March] that it will include Daewoo in the TGV (Train a Grand 
Vitesse) Korea consortium, currently comprising Hyundai, Hanjin, 
Goldstar and Samsung. 
  Daewoo, which said it had been assured a partnership role 
before Alsthom won the priority negotiating rights, later took 
the matter to court when it was left out of the TGV consortium. 
  GEC Alsthom promised that all five Korean companies will 
receive full technology transfers according to the Korean share 
of the project -- out of a total of 46, 34 TGV train sets will 
be produced in Korea. 
  The trains will be assembled and tested at Hyundai 
facilities: The engines (motor cars) produced equally by Hyundai 
and Daewoo: and the motorized carriages by Hanjin. 
  The technology and production of components such as traction 
motors, bogies and electrical equipment will be allocated to 
specialized companies, Alsthom said. 
  Goldstar and Samsung will participate in the signalling and 
traffic control systems. 

</TEXT>

