<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Increase in Technology Exports Reported </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1403022494 Seoul YONHAP in English 0142 GMT 14 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1403022494 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 14 (YONHAP) -- South Korea's technology 
exports are on the rise, business sources said Monday [14 March]. 
  Samsung Electronics Co. has exported 300 million U.S. 
dollars 
worth of technology and plants since 1990 and plans to export 
more than 20 kinds of technology to developing and developed 
countries this year. Samsung exported "synchronous D-ram" 
technology necessary to make 16 mega D-rams to Japan's Oki 
Electric Ind. Co. in February last year, as well as a 
95-million-dollar refrigerator plant to Kazakhstan along with 6 
million dollars in technology. 
  Goldstar Co. has exported 820,000 dollars worth of 
technology 
in the color television field since 1990 and expects to earn 
another 700,000 dollars from color TV technology this year. 
  Daewoo Electronics Co. exported a color television plant 
with 
an annual production capacity of 100,000 units and related 
technology to Iran Electric Industry (IEI) last year for 5 
million dollars. 
  In addition, SKC Ltd. exported 750,000 dollars in technology 
for assembling video cassette parts and for video cassette plant 
control to China last year. 
  Hyundai Motor Co. signed a Complete-Knock-Down (CKD) 
contract 
with a Malaysian Company to assemble and produce 1.25-ton trucks 
in January this year. Hyundai will receive royalties for each 
truck produced in Malaysia from the company. 
  Meanwhile, Dongbu Steel Co. Ltd. contracted with Germany's 
Wacker-Chemitronic Co. to export new processing technology for 
high-purity poly-christaline silicone last Tuesday. Dongbu will 
receive a 3.84-million-dollar technology fee and 1.0-2.5 percent 
of Wacker's total sales of the silicone products. 

</TEXT>

