<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Phone Accord Said No `Government Guarantee' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1503121894 Tokyo KYODO in English 1201 GMT 15 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1503121894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 15 KYODO -- The latest accord between 
Tokyo and Washington over cellular phone trade carries no 
government pledge guaranteeing results, a senior Trade Ministry 
official said Tuesday [15 March]. 
  What Japan agreed to do in the phone trade talks is not 
anything like a "government guarantee," said the official at the 
Ministry of International Trade and Industry, who declined to be 
identified. 
  The comment came in response to remarks by U.S. Trade 
Representative Mickey Kantor on Saturday's settlement of a 
dispute involving Motorola Inc. and Nippon Idou Tsushin Corp. 
(IDO) over the U.S. company's access to the Japanese cellular 
phone market. 
  Referring to part of the accord that says Tokyo will take 
"all available measures to ensure compliance with the 
commitments" undertaken by IDO, Kantor said the expression 
"validates the result-oriented approach" Washington wants in the 
future. 
  The MITI official said Japan cannot accept an interpretation 
that would lead to the setting of "numerical targets," an idea 
Tokyo has adamantly turned down in its trade talks with the 
United States. 
  MITI fears that the difference of interpretation between the 
two countries over the wording in question might develop into 
another source of bilateral contention, the official said. 
  Under the private-level agreement between IDO and Motorola 
that was reached before the governmental accord, the Japanese 
cellular phone company promised to open 159 new relay stations 
for Motorola-format phones. 

</TEXT>

