<H3> <TI>   Further Details Reported </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1503073194 Tokyo KYODO in English 0644 GMT 15 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1503073194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 15 KYODO -- Japan's merchandise trade 
surplus rose for a third straight month in February, climbing 
3.3 percent from a year before to 10,912 million dollars, the 
Finance Ministry said Tuesday [15 March] in a preliminary report. 
  The February rise in the customs-cleared trade surplus 
followed preliminary rises of 17.0 percent in January, 15.5 
percent in December and a 2.2 percent fall in November that 
snapped 34 months of consecutive year-on-year growth. 
  Exports rose 5.6 percent in February from a year earlier to 
29,532 million dollars, while imports rose 7.0 percent to 18,620 
million dollars, the ministry said. 
  Japan registered an unadjusted surplus of 4,344 million 
dollars in its trade with the United States. 

</TEXT>

