<H3> <TI>   Deregulation Panel Studies Information Sector </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1403045794 Tokyo KYODO in English 0356 GMT 14 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1403045794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 14 KYODO -- The administrative reform 
headquarters of Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa on Monday [14 
March] held its first meeting to discuss how to relax government 
regulations in information and telecommunications fields. 
  The premier urged an affiliated working group on information 
and telecommunications to propose ways to ease regulations in 
the two fields, Chief Cabinet Secretary Masayoshi Takemura told 
reporters. The panel was asked to report as soon as possible. 
  The group will meet once or twice a month and is expected to 
make its proposals by the end of June. The next meeting is 
scheduled for early April. 
  The group will weigh the possibility of developing an 
optical 
fiber-based communications network modeled after the national 
information infrastructure program of the U.S. Government, said 
Takeshi Fujii, chief of the Cabinet Councillor's Office on 
Internal Affairs. 

</TEXT>

