<H3> <TI>   MITI Seeks `Early' Accord With EU on Autos </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1403071894 Tokyo KYODO in English 0643 GMT 14 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1403071894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 14 KYODO -- Japan and the European 
Union (EU) should agree as early as possible on setting a 
ceiling for European-bound Japanese car exports for 1994, a 
senior Japanese trade ministry official said Monday [14 March]. 
  Japan's export ceiling for the year should be worked out 
before the next fiscal year starts on April 1, Hideaki Kumano, 
vice international trade and industry minister, told a press 
conference. 
  The comment came ahead of Japan-EU auto talks scheduled for 
Thursday and Friday in Tokyo, which are expected to discuss the 
size of auto demand in the EU in 1994, the benchmark for setting 
Japan's auto shipments to the union. 
  In talks in February, the two parties failed to narrow their 
difference on the prospects for demand for cars in the EU. The 
Europeans projected demand would level off, while the Japanese 
predicted a slight pickup. 
  The 1992 Japan-EU accord calls for the two sides to monitor 
Japanese car exports during a 1993-1999 transitional period 
before the EU auto market is fully liberalized in 2000. 

</TEXT>

