<H3> <TI>   Hosokawa, Ecuadoran President Discuss Loans </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1503141994 Tokyo KYODO in English 1354 GMT 15 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1503141994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 15 KYODO -- Ecuador President Sixto 
Duran-Ballen Cordovez called on Japan on Tuesday [15 March] to 
extend yen loans to the Latin American country to help its 
project to build up its power transmission network, Foreign 
Ministry officials said. 
  The president made the call in a 35-minute meeting with 
Prime 
Minister Morihiro Hosokawa, the officials said. 
  The meeting was followed by a 70-minute dinner at the prime 
minister's official residence. 
  Ecuador's project to set up branch lines from its main power 
grid and build transformer substations is estimated to cost a 
total of 90 million dollars, the officials said. 
  Duran-Ballen did not specify the amount of Japanese 
cooperation desired, they said. 
  Hosokawa told Duran-Ballen Japan will study the request for 
yen loans based on Ecuador's economic situation and debt, they 
said. 
  Duran-Ballen was quoted as saying ecuador will solve the 
debt 
problem as soon as possible so it can implement the power grid 
project. 
  During the meeting, the president also invited Hosokawa, 
Emperor Akihito and Empress Michiko, and Crown Prince Naruhito 
and Crown Princess Masako to visit Ecuador, the officials said. 
  He also invited them to visit Galapagos Island west of 
Ecuador, they said. 
  Hosokawa was quoted as saying Ecuador is a country he would 
like to visit sometime. 
  Hosokawa expressed the hope that relations between Japan and 
Ecuador would become even closer, the officials said. 
  He told the president the Japanese Government has been 
extending assistance to improve Ecuador's infrastructure and is 
currently studying possible cooperation in the nation's 
vocational training, the officials said. 
  A Japanese mission is visiting Ecuador between March 15 and 
26 to study the cooperation, Hosokawa was quoted as saying. 
  Hosokawa also said Japan will invite 10 young people from 
Ecuador for training in Japan, they said. 
  At the outset of the meeting, Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata 
and his counterpart from Ecuador Diego Paredes Pena exchanged 
documents on two Japanese grants-in-aid amounting to a total of 
1,123 million yen, according to the officials. 
  The assistance comprises 1,074 million yen for medical 
equipment in major hospitals and 49 million yen in cultural aid 
for equipment for the national sucre theater, they said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

