<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Hata Wants Two-Party System </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1403105394 Tokyo NHK General Television Network in 
Japanese 1000 GMT 13 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW1403105394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NHK General Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report: from the "NHK News 7" program] </F>
  [Text] Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata, at a news conference 
held today in Kanazawa City, where he is visiting on a stumping 
tour, expressed his hope again to form a new party to create a 
two-party system, in which change of power can be realized. 
  Foreign Minister Hata said: The coalition parties are 
working hard to steer the government. But, we just cannot 
continue indefinitely to keep the current process, in which the 
parties take every single issue to their own party for consensus 
before the coalition makes a decision as a while. 
  He then said: Rather than insisting on keeping our own 
party, I would like to form a strong and stable political force 
which can compete with the Liberal Democratic Party. I do not 
mind calling it a new new-party [shin shinto]. 
  In this way he renewed his willingness to form a two-party 
system, in which change of power can be realized. 

</TEXT>

