<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ruling Parties To Study Electoral Cooperation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1503040894 Tokyo NHK General Television Network in 
Japanese 1000 GMT 14 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW1503040894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NHK General Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report; from "NHK News 7" program] </F>
  [Text] At the meeting of the ruling coalition parties' 
representatives today, Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party] and 
Komeito suggested that the ruling parties should be reorganized 
into one party to facilitate electoral cooperation. It was 
decided that the ruling parties' representatives' meeting would 
serve as the venue for coordinating views on electoral 
cooperation and realignment of political parties. 
  During today's meeting, Shinseito representative Deputy 
Secretary General Kozo Watanabe, Komeito Secretary General 
Yuichi Ichikawa, and Democratic Socialist Party [DSP] Secretary 
General Takashi Yonezawa commented on the Social Democratic 
Party of Japan's [SDPJ] plan to unite the social democratic and 
liberal forces. They said that if there is no plan for the 
ruling parties to become one party in the future, electoral 
cooperation will not be possible in the upper house elections 
scheduled for summer 1995. They also pointed out that even in 
the lower house elections, it would be impossible to cooperate 
in the single-seat constituencies while competing in the 
proportional-representation constituencies. They indicated that 
it is necessary for the ruling parties to aim to form a new-new 
party [shin shin to] to campaign effectively in the forthcoming 
elections. 
  In response, SDPJ Secretary General Wataru Kubo said, it is 
still a viable method of electoral cooperation for the ruling 
parties to coordinate on the choice of candidates and cooperate 
with each other in the elections. He stated that it is not 
possible to proceed right away to form a new-new party. 
  In light of these differing views, the ruling coalition 
parties decided to use representatives' meetings or party heads' 
meetings as venues to coordinate views on electoral cooperation, 
and to discuss the closely-related issue of the realignment of 
political parties for the time being. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

