<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ouchi Advocates Early Realignment of Parties </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1503092894 Tokyo KYODO in English 0858 GMT 15 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1503092894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 15 KYODO -- Keigo Ouchi, chairman of 
the Democratic Socialist Party (DSP), advocates an early 
realignment of Japanese political parties to prepare for general 
elections which he says could take place anytime after January 
1995. 
  He said in an interview with KYODO NEWS SERVICE that 
political parties should realign by this summer to allow time to 
hammer out policies and prepare candidates for the House of 
Representatives elections. 
  "The elections for the House of Councillors are planned for 
next summer and general elections (for the lower house) under 
the new electoral system could take place anytime after January 
next year," Ouchi said. 
  The DSP chief said the biggest challenge facing Japanese 
politics today is to lay the foundation for one or two political 
parties that could take over the reins of government from the 
largest opposition Liberal Democratic Party (LDP). 
  The LDP ruled for 38 years until Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa, head of the fledgling Japan New Party, launched a 
seven-party coalition last summer. 
  Ouchi praised Hosokawa for making a "courageous decision" 
not 
to reshuffle his cabinet, a move aimed chiefly at getting rid of 
Chief Cabinet Secretary Masayoshi Takemura, the head of new 
party Sakigake. 
  He said in the interview that the Hosokawa administration 
would have fallen apart if it had proceeded with a 7 percent 
national welfare tax program and a cabinet shake-up. 
  Ouchi blamed Shinseito secretary general Ichiro Ozawa and 
his 
Komeito counterpart Yuichi Ichikawa for the ill-fated scenarios, 
and said such high-handed politicking could lead to a collapse 
of the coalition government. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

