<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Issue Threatens Budget Debate </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1403143894 Tokyo KYODO in English 1359 GMT 14 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1403143894 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> ["News focus" by Takehiko Kajita: "Hosokawa's Loan Dispute </F>
Delays Debate on Key Budget"] 
  [Text] Tokyo, March 14 KYODO -- Prime Minister Morihiro 
Hosokawa's failure to give a clear-cut account of his loan from 
a scandal-plagued firm has not only fueled a spat between the 
ruling coalition and the opposition camp, but has delayed 
parliamentary debate on the key fiscal 1994 state budget. 
  "With the question of politicians and money drawing 
attention, Mr. Hosokawa has not told the truth of whether he was 
given the money or borrowed it, leaving the matter unresolved," 
Yoshiro Mori, secretary general of the main opposition Liberal 
Democratic Party (LDP) said Sunday [13 March]. 
  Mori, in a move to throw down the gauntlet to the governing 
coalition, warned that his party will refuse to begin a session 
of the House of Representatives Budget Committee to discuss the 
national budget for fiscal 1994, starting April 1, until the 
premier proves his innocence. 
  Hosokawa has insisted he borrowed the 100 million yen from 
Tokyo Sagawa Kyubin Co., a now-defunct parcel delivery company, 
in 1982 and repaid the money nine years later. But the LDP, 
toppled from power last summer for the first time in nearly four 
decades, has retorted it is unclear how the premier used the 
money and how he returned it to the creditor. 
  Tokyo Sagawa Kyubin, which has since been absorbed into 
Sagawa Kyubin Co., a Kyoto-based parent company, was embroiled 
in a massive money-and-mob scandal in 1992 and 1993 that 
implicated former Prime Minister Noboru Takeshita and disgraced 
LDP kingmaker Shin Kanemaru. 
  One element compounding the matter is Hosokawa's 
inconsistent 
and less-than persuasive explanations about his receipt and 
repayment of the money. This has caused the LDP to suspect that 
it was not a loan that the premier obtained, but an illicit 
donation. 
  Last December, Hosokawa said in a memo to the Diet that he 
borrowed the 100 million yen from Kiyoshi Sagawa, former 
chairman of Sagawa Kyubin, through Tokyo Sagawa in September 
1982 to buy a condominium in Tokyo and repair his home in 
Kumamoto Prefecture, southwestern Japan. 
  He also explained he paid back the money by January 31, 
1991, 
using part of his retirement allowance as Kumamoto governor, in 
addition to using the proceeds from the sale of a plot of land 
in Tokyo. 
  But the LDP has pointed out that Hosokawa could not have 
received the retirement allowance before he finished his second 
four-year term as governor in February 1991, raising doubts 
about the premier's accounts. 
  With the memo also showing that Hosokawa purchased the Tokyo 
condominium in July 1982, two months before he borrowed the 
money from Sagawa, the LDP and the Japanese Communist Party 
(JCP) have charged that the premier used the money to secure his 
campaign funds for a Kumamoto gubernatorial election one year 
later. 
  Furthermore, Hosokawa's failure to submit to the Diet all 
the 
receipts he must have accepted from Sagawa if he really repaid 
the money sparked a barrage of criticism from the opposition 
camp that the premier took the money as an illegal political 
donation, not as what he insists was a loan. 
  Dissatisfied with Hosokawa's explanations, the LDP and the 
JCP successfully forced the lower house budget panel, in an 
unusual move, to ask the government to submit to the Diet 
detailed documents concerning Hosokawa's payment of the Sagawa 
money. 
  Although the government presented some documents relating to 
the loan last Friday, the two parties laughed them off and 
refused to set a timetable for Diet discussion on the key budget 
unless the government submits further detailed documents. 
  "If Mr. Hosokawa can have the public understand he really 
paid back the money, we believe we do not have to question him 
any further and discuss this matter any longer," Sadatoshi 
Ozato, chairman of the LDP Diet Affairs Committee, said Monday. 
  "But he has only widened doubts regarding the question of 
how 
specifically he returned it," Ozato said, adding that the party 
will leave the matter of setting a schedule of budget discussion 
up to a group of directors of the lower house budget panel for a 
little longer. 
  The government and the ruling coalition aim to have the 
fiscal 1994 national budget passed through the Diet by mid-May 
and minimize the effects of the delayed Diet deliberations on 
the ailing Japanese economy. 
  As Hosokawa postponed the formulation of the budget from the 
end of last year till early this year to concentrate on Diet 
deliberations on his cherished political reform, the start of 
budget debate has been delayed until mid-March or later for the 
first time since 1967. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

