<H3> <TI>   FTC Suspects Four Dailies of Violating Law </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1503132594 Tokyo KYODO in English 1310 GMT 15 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1503132594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 15 KYODO -- The Fair Trade Commission 
(FTC) has ordered four major newspaper companies to report why 
they raised subscription fees, suspecting them of violating the 
Antimonopoly Law, FTC officials said Tuesday [15 March]. 
  The ASAHI SHIMBUN and the MAINICHI SHIMBUN raised 
subscription fees last December and the YOMIURI SHIMBUN in 
January, all by 200 yen per month. The NIHON KEIZAI SHIMBUN 
raised its monthly subscription fee by 300 yen in February. 
  The FTC suspect the four major dailies colluded in 
increasing 
the fees, the officials said. 
  The Antimonopoly Law stipulates that a concerted price hike 
occurs if two of the top five firms in a sector with a market of 
60 billion yen or more in which the top three firms together 
account for a share of more than 70 percent, raise prices of 
their goods within three months of each other. 

</TEXT>

