<H3> <TI>   FTC Orders 25 Firms To Pay for Bid Rigging </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1403083194 Tokyo KYODO in English 0804 GMT 14 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1403083194 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 14 KYODO -- The Fair Trade Commission 
(FTC) ordered 25 water supply meter equipment manufacturers 
Monday [14 March] to pay a 180 million yen penalty for their 
involvement in a bid-rigging affair, FTC officials said. 
  The 25 companies were found to have violated the 
antimonopoly 
law by rigging bids on orders from the Tokyo Metropolitan 
Government, 15 municipal and town authorities in Osaka 
Prefecture and 16 municipal, town and village administrations in 
Fukuoka Prefecture, the officials said. 
  Among the 25 firms were the Tokyo-based Kimmon Mfg. Co., the 
Nagoya-based Aichi Tokei Denki Co., the Kyoto-based Nitto Seiko 
Co., and OKK corp. and Toko Co., both based in Osaka. 
  Over the years, the 25 firms held meetings to conspire in 
determining who would be awarded orders from local 
administrations and what prices would be set on equipment. 

</TEXT>

