<H3> <TI>   Central Bank Reports Economic Figures for Feb </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1403105494 Tokyo KYODO in English 1020 GMT 14 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1403105494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 14 KYODO -- Japan's wholesale prices 
fell 0.5 percent in February from the previous month, the Bank 
of Japan said Monday [14 March]. 
  The overall wholesale price index came to 93.5 against the 
base of 100 for 1990. 
  On a year-to-year basis, the index slid 3.2 percent. 
  Domestic wholesale prices in February were unchanged from 
the 
previous month but retreated 2.0 percent from a year earlier. 
  Export prices for February fell 0.1 percent from the 
previous 
month on a contract currency basis and moved down 3.3 percent in 
yen terms. 
  Import prices edged up 0.8 percent on a contract currency 
basis but declined 2.3 percent in yen terms from January. 
  A Bank of Japan official said export prices on a contract 
currency basis fell for the first time since December 1992 as 
price-raising moves following the sharp appreciation of the yen 
against the dollar last year came to a halt. 
  Import prices on a contract currency basis moved up from the 
month before due to higher commodity prices overseas but they 
declined in yen terms because of the yen's appreciation, he said. 
  The dollar averaged 106.25 yen in the month, falling 4.8 
percent from January and down 12.3 percent from a year before. 
  The official said domestic wholesale prices remain stable 
and 
attributed the levelling off from the previous in contrast to 
continued declines since last July to higher overseas commodity 
prices. 
  But commodity prices are already coming down, the official 
said, adding that the index is unlikely to continue moving up. 
  The wholesale price index for rice stood at 112.0 against 
the 
base of 100 for 1990, continuing to stay high since last autumn 
because of the poor harvest, the official said. The index was 
102.2 in August, before it began to go up. 
  It remained unchanged from January, however, in spite of 
higher prices reported at the retail level. The statistics do 
not include prices of imported rice, the official said. 

</TEXT>

