<F P=100> Thailand </F>
<H3> <TI>   Security Increased at Interior Ministry </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK1403034894 Bangkok BANGKOK POST in English 14 Mar 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> BK1403034894 </F>
<F P=104>  Bangkok BANGKOK POST </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Excerpt] Security at the Interior Ministry will be stepped 
up from today, with the offices of Interior Minister Chawalit 
Yongchaiyut being declared a "restricted zone". The offices of 
the five deputy interior ministers, the permanent secretary and 
deputy permanent secretaries have also been declared "restricted 
zones", where unauthorised entry is prohibited. 
  A source said yesterday the tightening of security at the 
ministry was agreed on at a meeting on Friday in the aftermath 
of bomb attacks on the homes of Social Action Party [SAP] leader 
Montri Phongpanit, SAP MP Bunphan Khaewatthana, Permanent Labour 
Secretary Sawai Phrammani in Nakhon Ratchasima and on a 
locomotive in Songkhla. 
  As part of the new measures, the source said, the offices in 
the Interior Ministry of the Local Administration Department, 
the Secretariat, the Permanent Secretary, the Welfare and Labour 
Protection Department and the Institute of Prince Damrong 
Rachanuphap are now regarded as restricted zones. Earlier, 
Permanent Interior Secretary Aree Wong-araya had declared his 
office and the area in front of it off-limits to reporters. 
[passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

