<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   IAEA Inspectors Finish Inspection, Depart </TI></H3>
<H4>   Official Cited on Inspection </H4>
<F P=102> SK1503000694 Seoul YONHAP in English 2359 GMT 14 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1503000694 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Berlin, March 14 (YONHAP) -- The International 
Atomic Energy Agency's [IAEA] inspection team finished its work 
in North Korea Monday and is scheduled to leave Pyongyang for 
Vienna Tuesday, IAEA officials said. 
  The IAEA team had studied the possibility of leaving some 
inspectors behind to handle the transport of equipment and 
samples weighing about 300 kilograms, but decided against it, 
the officials said. 
  An IAEA official stressed that the idea of leaving some 
members behind had been contemplated purely because of equipment 
shipping problems. He said he understood that the inspection 
work had proceeded without a hitch so far. 
  The official added, however, that he did not know whether 
the 
team had carried out all of its inspection plans. 
  One of the inspectors has already gone to Vienna and the 
remaining six are scheduled to return on Thursday via Beijing. 
  The IAEA's nuclear safeguards bureau will receive a report 
from the team before submitting its own report to 
Director-General Hans Blix on whether there was any change in 
the North Korean situation. The report will help determine the 
need for convening a special Board of Governors meeting, they 
said. 
  At the regular Board of Governors meeting in February, the 
IAEA agreed to call a special meeting if the inspection team's 
activities were restricted or if it determined that continuity 
in nuclear safeguards had been disrupted in North Korea. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-6255 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "dreas050_d_94002" </HT>


