<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   IAEA Inspectors Finish Inspection, Depart </TI></H3>
<H4>   Kyd Calls Inspection `Unsatisfactory' </H4>
<F P=102> SK1403224994 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 2210 GMT 14 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK1403224994 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Korean </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Cha Man-sun from Vienna] </F>
  [Text] The International Atomic Energy Agency [IAEA] 
inspection team will leave Pyongyang on 15 March after finishing 
its 12-day inspection of North Korea. 
  David Kyd, IAEA information director, said: On 14 March, the 
inspection team completed its activities in Yongbyon, which 
started on 3 March in response to an emergency order from the 
IAEA Secretariat. The team will depart Pyongyang on 15 March 
and return to Vienna via Beijing on 16 March. 
  The IAEA is now considering convening a special Board of 
Governors meeting next week after notifying major board members 
that the recent inspection activities were unsatisfactory 
[manjoksuropchi motaessumul]. 
  Major board members decided that the recent inspection of 
North Korea was not sufficient [mihup] to determine if nuclear 
materials are being used for other purposes because it was 
difficult to collect sample materials due to North Korea's 
uncooperative attitude [pukhanui pihyopchoro]. Accordingly, it 
seems to be inevitable that a special Board of Governors meeting 
will be convened next week. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

