<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ozawa Cancels `Troubleshooting' Mission to U.S. </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1503123494 Tokyo KYODO in English 1221 GMT 15 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1503123494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 15 KYODO -- The ruling coalition's 
chief strategist, Ichiro Ozawa, said Tuesday [15 March] he has 
canceled a journey to the United States later this month. 
  Ozawa told a group of reporters in the Diet that it would be 
difficult because he has not made any preparations for the trip. 
His U.S. visit was believed to be a troubleshooting mission to 
find a breakthrough in the strained Japan-U.S. trade ties. 
  Secretary general of the coalition's primary bloc Shinseito 
and a close associate of Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa, Ozawa 
initially considered going to Washington on March 21 at the 
request of the National Press Club to deliver a speech. 
  Ozawa, however, had eyed using the opportunity to meet 
officials in the administration of President Bill Clinton and 
congressional leaders to work out difficulties that hampered the 
development of bilateral economic ties following the failure of 
the "framework" trade talks last month, political sources said. 
Hosokawa and Clinton failed to reach agreement in the talks 
aimed at opening up Japan's market to U.S. goods and reducing 
its huge trade surplus. 
  On the possibility of visiting the U.S. in the future, Ozawa 
said he would consider going after the intense media speculation 
over the trip has died down. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

