<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   U.S. Demand for Overcharges Repayment Viewed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1503053694 Tokyo NHK General Television Network in 
Japanese 0306 GMT 15 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> OW1503053694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo NHK General Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Announcer-read report; from "NHK News" program] </F>
  [Text] It has been revealed that concerning construction 
projects at the U.S. Forces Japan [USFJ] Atsugi base, the U.S. 
Government has notified the Japanese Government of its intention 
to demand that 73 Japanese construction companies pay a total of 
1.1 billion yen in compensation for its having been forced to 
pay unreasonably high construction costs as a result of bid 
rigging among major Japanese construction companies. 
  According to the message, the U.S. Government has been 
unjustly forced to pay unusually high costs for the construction 
of facilities at the USFJ Atsugi base in Kanagawa Prefecture 
between 1984 and 1990 because major Japanese construction 
companies engaged in bid rigging. It is reported that the U.S. 
Government therefore intends to demand about 1.1 billion yen in 
compensation from 73 construction companies which were involved 
in the construction projects. 
  In this regard, Construction Minister Kozo Igarashi said at 
a 
news conference following a cabinet meeting this morning that 
although it is the job of the Fair Trade Commission to determine 
whether there was bid rigging, the Construction Ministry, for 
its part, will immediately investigate the matter. Igarashi, 
however, brushed aside concerns that this situation might refuel 
bilateral construction frictions, saying that it would not 
affect future bilateral ties because Japan presented the United 
States with measures last January to improve foreign access to 
Japanese construction markets, including the revision of bidding 
procedures, and that the two nations managed to reach an accord. 
  Meanwhile, the Foreign Ministry feels the United States is 
not linking the bid rigging issue to the ongoing bilateral 
economic disputes because this matter is strictly a civil issue. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

