<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Concern Voiced Over DPRK-IAEA Issue </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1703114294 Tokyo KYODO in English 1124 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1703114294 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 17 KYODO -- Japan voiced concern 
Thursday [17 March] over North Korea's reported obstruction of 
international inspections at one of its nuclear facilities. "We 
can't but feel concerned that North Korea did not fully and 
sincerely uphold its agreement with the IAEA (International 
Atomic Energy Agency) and that diversion of nuclear material for 
military purposes could not be verified," Foreign Minister 
Tsutomu Hata told a press conference. 
  Chief Cabinet Secretary Masayoshi Takemura also said during 
an earlier press conference that Japan is "deeply concerned." 
  The IAEA said Wednesday Pyongyang obstructed checks at a key 
nuclear facility and that the agency would hold a special 
meeting of its board of governors next Monday, as the 
long-standing nuclear controversy with North Korea soared to new 
heights. 
  The Vienna-based international nuclear watchdog said North 
Korea barred a team of its inspectors from carrying out 
"important measures" at a radiochemical laboratory in Yongbyon 
which the IAEA regards as a nuclear reprocessing plant. 
  The United States also said a third round of talks with 
North 
Korea, scheduled for next Monday in Geneva, would be postponed 
due to North Korea's refusal to cooperate. 
  Hata and Takemura both cited the necessity of renewed calls 
to North Korea to completely accept international inspections of 
all its facilities. Hata said the problem of North Korea's 
suspected nuclear program would naturally be discussed when 
Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa visits China from Saturday to 
Monday. 
  Government officials have said Hosokawa is expected to call 
for China's continued role in persuading Pyongyang to accept 
full inspections to sweep away international concern over its 
alleged nuclear program. 
  Hata said Japan wants to seek a solution to the problem 
through negotiations. He declined to say what the Japanese 
Government would do if the IAEA meeting adopted a resolution 
referring the matter to the United Nations Security Council, 
saying it is too early to comment. 
  If the IAEA meeting declares North Korea in breach of 
nuclear 
safeguard accords, the matter would be referred to the U.N. 
Security Council, which might impose economic sanctions on 
Pyongyang. 
  A South Korean Foreign Ministry official said Thursday that 
the nuclear watchdog is likely to demand that North Korea grant 
complete inspections of its radiochemical laboratory instead of 
opting for sanctions. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

