<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   ROK Said Not To Reduce Shipbuilding Capacity </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1603125494 Tokyo KYODO in English 1152 GMT 16 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1603125494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 16 KYODO -- The South Korean 
shipbuilding industry has not agreed to exercise self-restraint 
in stepping up their shipbuilding capacity in talks held between 
industry leaders of Japan, South Korea and Europe, a Japanese 
industry leader said Wednesday [16 March]. "The three sides 
could not reach an agreement," said Shigeru Goda, chairman of 
the Shipbuilders Association of Japan, at a regular press 
conference. 
  Japan and Europe have been asking South Korea to voluntarily 
reduce its shipbuilding capacity which has strengthened 
noticeably this year since the abolition in late 1993 of a South 
Korean law restricting the growth of shipbuilding capacity. The 
South Korean shipbuilding industry has become even more 
conspicuous as the competitiveness of Japanese shipbuilders has 
declined with the appreciation of the Japanese currency. 
  Goda said that during the Japan-South Korea, and Japan-South 
Korea-Europe talks held from March 12 to 14, Japanese and 
European officials said the global shipbuilding industry would 
be able to meet future demand at the current level of 
shipbuilding capacity. They pointed to the danger of excess 
shipbuilding capacity leading to lower prices and an eventual 
slump in the industry, Goda said. 
  South Korea responded that their government is pursuing a 
policy of easing restrictions, and that they have no intention 
of extending their share of the market by cheaper prices, Goda 
said. 
  In 1993, South Korea surpassed Japan to become the world's 
largest shipbuilder, with orders totaling 9.52 million tons. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

