<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tokyo Gives Loan, Disaster Relief Goods to Peru </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1603002994 Tokyo KYODO in English 2258 GMT 15 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1603002994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 16 KYODO -- Japan will loan Peru up to 
2.24 billion yen to cooperate in its project to beef up its 
public welfare services, Foreign Ministry officials said 
Wednesday [16 March]. Japanese Parliamentary Vice Foreign 
Minister Syozo Azuma and Peruvian Prime Minister and Foreign 
Minister Efrain Gordenberg Schreiber exchanged documents on the 
Japanese loan in Lima. 
  Azuma told Gordenberg the Japanese Government will provide 
emergency relief materials worth 19 million yen to help the 
victims of heavy rains, which have killed more than 71 people in 
Peru. The loan, to be extended in coordination with the 
Inter-American Development Bank (IDB), will be used for Peru's 
program to improve and modernize the basic equipment in public 
medical organizations which offer medical services to people on 
low incomes, the officials said. 
  Because of the lack of basic medical equipment and funds, 
there are insufficient medical services for such people in Peru, 
and epidemics such as cholera and malaria are common in the 
country. 
  The 30-year loan, with a 10-year grace period, carries an 
annual interest rate of 3 percent. It brings the total amount 
of Japanese loans extended to the Latin American nation to 
153.87 billion yen, the officials said. 
  The emergency relief materials from Japan include blankets, 
tents and medical goods, they said. 
  According to the officials, heavy rains have been falling on 
the mountainous regions of Peru since mid-January. As of March 
1, the subsequent floods and landslides had killed 71 people and 
affected another 70,000. 
  The officials said the Peruvian Government has requested 
emergency relief goods from Japan. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

