<H3> <TI>   Hata Apologizes for Confusion Over Rice Supply </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1703041994 Tokyo KYODO in English 0401 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1703041994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 17 KYODO -- Agriculture, Forestry and 
Fisheries Minister Eijiro Hata apologized Thursday for confusion 
over the supply of rice and assured consumers that there will 
not be any serious shortage. 
  Speaking before the House of Councillors' Committee on 
Agriculture, Forestry and Fisheries, Hata said there will not be 
any "quantitative problem" because the government has secured 
rice to meet needs until August. Hata was replying to a 
question by an opposition lawmaker about the mounting public 
outrage as Japanese rice has disappeared from store shelves and 
many consumers shun imported rice. 
  Hata said a total of three million tons of rice is needed 
for 
consumption until August and the need will be fulfilled by some 
1.2 million tons of domestically grown rice left in stock, 1.7 
million tons in imports and 100,000 tons of early crop rice from 
this year's harvest. The government will step up efforts to 
import more rice, he said. 

</TEXT>

