<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   FTC Orders Penalties for Aerial Survey Firms </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1703105994 Tokyo KYODO in English 1041 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1703105994 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 17 KYODO -- The Fair Trade Commission 
(FTC) ordered 29 aerial survey contractors to pay penalties 
totaling 790 million yen for bid-rigging practices that it says 
violated the Antimonopoly Law, commission officials said 
Thursday [17 March]. The companies include such leading firms 
as Pasco Corp., Asia Air Survey Co. and Kokusai Kogyo Co. 
  Pasco and Asia Air Survey Co. were each told to pay 200 
million yen, the highest penalty ever brought against a private 
company for bid-rigging in relation to public works projects. 
  The total of fines also marks the third highest sought by 
the 
FTC in such cases. The highest penalties in a bid-rigging case 
totaled some 1 billion yen against contractors in Saitama 
Prefecture, near Tokyo, in 1992. 
  The FTC said the aerial survey companies, through one 
Tokyo-based land measurement association, continued prearranged 
biddings from around 1984 for map production orders placed by 
the Construction Ministry's Geographical Survey Institute. 
  The firms also arranged illegal bidding for tenders held by 
the government and municipal governments for aerial photographic 
surveys from 1988 to 1992. They reportedly set up intercompany 
cooperative bodies in several regions to fix successful bidders 
and contract prices beforehand, the commission said. 
  In February 1993, the FTC ordered the contractors and 
association to end bid-rigging practices. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

