<H3> <TI>   Central Bank Reports Feb Money Supply Rise </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1703092594 Tokyo KYODO in English 0841 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1703092594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 17 KYODO -- Japan's benchmark money 
supply grew 1.6 percent in February on a year-to-year basis, the 
Bank of Japan said in a preliminary report Thursday [17 March]. 
  The M2 and certificates of deposit (CDs) gained a revised 
1.6 
percent in January, marking the first growth pace pickup in four 
months. M2 is cash in circulation plus demand and time deposits. 
  The broader measure of liquidity, including postal savings, 
government debts and investment trusts, expanded 3.0 percent in 
February over a year before, compared with a 3.0 percent rise in 
January. 

</TEXT>

