<F P=100> Vietnam </F>
<H3> <TI>   Thai Delegation Visit, Leadership Meetings Noted </TI></H3>
<H4>   Fishing Rights Discussed </H4>
<F P=102> BK1703014494 Bangkok BANGKOK POST in English 17 Mar 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> BK1703014494 </F>
<F P=104>  Bangkok BANGKOK POST </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By Suphaphon Kanwirayothin in Hanoi] </F>
  [Excerpts] Thailand and Vietnam, in a bid to remove a major 
thorn in bilateral relations, yesterday agreed to set up a joint 
task force at ministerial level to resolve the problem of 
fishing rights in the Gulf of Thailand. They agreed on the move, 
which was proposed by Thailand, during talks held shortly after 
the arrival here of Prime Minister Chuan Likphai for a four-day 
official visit. 
  Fishery questions topped the agenda of a dozen issues the 
two 
delegations touched on during the plenary talks chaired by Mr 
Chuan and Vietnam's Premier Vo Van Kiet. Fisheries Department 
chief Plotprasop Suratsawat affirmed Thailand's eagerness to 
settle the fishery row. He told the BANGKOK POST he hoped the 
joint task force would be able to recommend a solution within 
the first two months of its inception. "Both sides shared the 
feeling that this problem must be resolved urgently but with 
extreme caution as it has implications encompassing aspects of 
national security, economy and the livelihoods of the two 
peoples. And a rash solution could be damaging," Mr Plotprasop 
said. [passage omitted] 
  The question of fishing rights will be discussed in depth 
today in a separate meeting between Foreign Minister Prasong 
Sunsiri and his Vietnamese counterpart Nguyen Manh Cam. Mr 
Plotprasop will also attend the meeting. According to Mr 
Plotprasop, the Thai delegation yesterday made clear to the 
Vietnamese side that if there were no solution to the fishery 
problem, cooperation in other fields might be affected, for 
instance that of agriculture. [passage omitted] 
  Meanwhile, Defence Minister Wichit Sukmak is due to hold 
bilateral talks with Vietnam's Defence Minister Doan Khue this 
morning. 

</TEXT>

