<F P=100> Vietnam </F>
<H3> <TI>   Thai Delegation Visit, Leadership Meetings Noted </TI></H3>
<H4>   Further on Do Muoi-Chuan Meeting </H4>
<F P=102> BK1703053294 Bangkok Radio Thailand Network in Thai 0000 GMT 
17 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1703053294 </F>
<F P=104>  Bangkok Radio Thailand Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Thai </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prime Minister Chuan Likphai paid a courtesy call on 
Do Muoi, general secretary of the Communist Party of Vietnam 
[CPV], at the party Central Committee Office in Hanoi at 1700 
yesterday. Both the CPV general secretary and the Thai prime 
minister agreed that both countries will follow up agreements 
reached in various fields so they will bear fruit effectively. 
  On the same occasion, the CPV general secretary expressed 
his 
admiration to His Majesty the King and members of the royal 
family of Thailand. The CPV general secretary greatly admired 
the royally initiated projects dealing with agriculture and 
water resources and he wants to request Thai assistance on this 
field. Aphisit Wetchachiwa, spokesman of the Prime Minister's 
Office, granted an interview to this reporter on the event. 
  [Begin recording] [Aphisit] The Vietnamese party Central 
Committee general secretary expressed his profound admiration 
and gratitude to His Majesty the King, who once granted him an 
audience. He also expressed his admiration to members of the 
Thai Royal Family and royally initiated projects in various 
fields. He noted that the relationship between the two 
countries has significantly improved in the past few years. He 
wanted the bilateral cooperation to further develop for 
economic, social, and political interests in this region. 
  [Unidentified reporter] What royally initiated projects is 
the CPV chairman [as heard] interested in and admires? 
  [Aphisit] He said he is greatly impressed by royally 
initiated projects, especially in the field of agriculture 
dealing with water. This is because Vietnam wants to improve 
agricultural production efficiency. Despite success at a 
certain level in economic reform, Vietnam still has problems due 
to a lack of technology and improvement in production 
efficiency, which is becoming more competitive. He specifically 
admired the king's ability in agriculture and royally initiated 
projects in various fields. 
  [Reporter] [Question indistinct] 
  [Aphisit] He mentioned Thailand providing assistance 
through royally initiated projects to other countries, such as 
Laos. Such forms of assistance are aimed to be models. Vietnam 
has also requested such assistance from Thailand. 
  [Reporter] Does he want royally initiated projects to be in 
his country? 
  [Aphisit] Right. 
  [Reporter] Did they discuss possible steps to be taken? 
  [Aphisit] The king will be informed of this matter and I 
think it could be possible because the king also mentioned this 
in an audience once given to him. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

