<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Official: Continuity of Safeguards Not Problem </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1703051194 Seoul YONHAP in English 0502 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1703051194 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 17 (YONHAP) -- The International Atomic 
Energy Agency (IAEA) failed to verify that North Korea had not 
diverted nuclear material, but most likely kept alive the 
continuous flow of inspections, a Foreign Ministry official said 
here Thursday. 
  "The IAEA did not say anything specific on that part," Ham 
Myong-chol, director-general of the International Organizations 
Bureau, said when asked if IAEA safeguards in North Korea had 
been compromised. 
  "The agency only concluded that it could not verify the 
diversion, but it seems that there wasn't a problem on that part 
(continuity of safeguards) of the issue," he said. 
  If true, the international community would still have room 
for diplomatic negotiations with North Korea on resolving the 
inspection issue before taking it to the Security Council for 
punitive measures. 
  The IAEA issued a statement from its Vienna headquarters 
that 
its inspectors were not allowed full access to the North Korean 
radiochemical laboratory, regarded by the agency as a nuclear 
reprocessing plant and the key part of Pyongyang's covert 
weapons program. 
  The U.N. agency has decided to convene a special Board of 
Governors meeting on March 21. 
  Ham said the inspectors saw all but a few important parts of 
the radiochemical laboratory. "The question of diversion will 
be the key issue at the March 21 meeting," he said. 
  The results of the meeting will be reported automatically to 
the U.N. Security Council, which alone must decide on whether to 
intervene, Ham said. 
  The IAEA board is expected to adopt a resolution expressing 
concern and regret over the restricted inspections and demanding 
immediate access to relevant areas, he said. 

</TEXT>

