<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   `Strong Measures' Considered on Nuclear Issue </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1703094494 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 0900 GMT 17 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK1703094494 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Korean </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The government is in the process of actively 
considering taking strong measures by mobilizing all possible 
means, including handing this issue over to the UN Security 
Council and imposing sanctions on North Korea, if North Korea 
does not respond to an additional inspection by the 
International Atomic Energy Agency and the South-North exchange 
of special envoys. 
  In a news conference on the afternoon of 17 March, Kim 
Sam-hun, nuclear ambassador of the Foreign Ministry, revealed 
such a policy by saying that the government has strong doubts on 
whether it should continue its dialogue efforts with North Korea 
and if that is possible at all. He also stated that now is the 
time to take all possible proper steps. 
  In connection with resolving North Korea's nuclear issue, he 
said that the government's policy on the North Korean nuclear 
issue maintained the basic framework of peaceful resolution 
through dialogue in the past. However, the government's policy 
revealed today is very noteworthy because it hints that the 
government's policy on North Korea will turn to strong measures, 
including sanctions. 

</TEXT>

