<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minister, Wisner on Countermeasures for DPRK </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1703070194 Seoul YONHAP in English 0636 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1703070194 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 17 (YONHAP) -- Foreign Minister Han 
Sung-chu and U.S. Undersecretary of Defense Frank Wisner 
discussed initiating a new phase of countermeasures in the North 
Korean nuclear dispute, Foreign Ministry officials said Thursday. 
  Wisner, in Seoul since Monday, met with Han for an hour-long 
talk to evaluate the current crisis over nuclear inspections in 
the North and stalled inter-Korean dialogue, said Chang 
Chae-yong, director-general of the American Affairs Bureau. 
  The two officials discussed what to expect next -- either 
North Korea meeting the South Korean and U.S. demands or 
continuing with its present attitude of refusal, he said. 
  In case of the latter, Han and Wisner agreed their countries 
may need to enter into a new phase of countermeasures. 
  "Countermeasures are under preparation for such an event," 
Chang said. 
  Asked whether they talked about deployment of Patriot 
missiles and resuming this year's South Korea-U.S. joint 
military drill "Team Spirit," Chang indirectly said yes by 
adding, "of course, issues related to security in light of the 
present situation were addressed." 

</TEXT>

