<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   DPRK To Designate Second Free Economic Zone </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1703013494 Seoul YONHAP in English 0050 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1703013494 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 17 (YONHAP) -- North Korea has 
reportedly made an unofficial decision to designate the 
northwestern coast from Sinuiju to Nampo as its second free 
economic zone. 
  Pyongyang earlier sent officials to study China's coastal 
economic zones, who came to realize that the current 
Najin-Sonbong free trade zone on the northeastern coast was too 
regionally closed and less attractive to foreign investors due 
to insufficient infrastructure, according to a report by the 
Korea Trade Promotion Corp. (Kotra) representative in Beijing. 
  Instead, the North Koreans are expected to designate the 
northwestern coast bewtween Nampo and Sinuiju, which is adjacent 
to China, as a new economic zone. 
  North Korea has already started moving residents near the 
Amnok River and Sinuiju and is preparing to build a railway 
linking the far Western coastal city with Pyongyang. 
  The Stalinist country is expected to announce the opening of 
the two port cities on Sept. 9, timed with its 46th anniversary. 
  Once Sinuiju and Nampo are named a free economic zone, the 
area is likely to draw more foreign investment than the 
Najin-Sonbong zone in the initial stage, Kotra officials said. 
  The Najin-Sonbong zone is expected to be developed as a 
center for export-oriented industry and entrepot trade, while 
the Sinuiju-Nampo area will be promoted as a complex for light 
industry, the officials said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

