<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   DLP Delegates To Visit China Last Half of 1994 </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1703101694 Seoul YONHAP in English 0744 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1703101694 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul YONHAP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Seoul, March 17 (YONHAP) -- The chairman of the 
ruling Democratic Liberal Party, Kim Chong-pil, will visit China 
in the second half of this year at the invitation of the Chinese 
Communist Party, preceded by DLP Secretary-general Mun Chong-su, 
who may travel to Beijing as early as April. 
  DLP Deputy Secretary-general Cho Pu-yong met with the deputy 
head of the International Liaison Department of the Chinese 
Communist Party, Zhu Shanqing, on Thursday here to discuss 
expanding cooperation and exchanges. At the working-level 
meeting, the two sides agreed that the DLP will send a five- to 
seven-member mission led by Secretary-general Mun to China as 
early as April. 
  But DLP Chairman Kim's visit to Beijing, which was scheduled 
for the first half of the year, has been postponed to the second 
half because President Kim Yong-sam will go to China soon. 
  In return for Mun's visit to China, Beijing will send a 
high-level delegation to Seoul headed by a party Politburo 
member or cabinet minister. 

</TEXT>

