<F P=100> AUSTRALASIA </F>
<F P=101> Australia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Increased Growth Rate Shows Economic Recovery </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  BK1603091894 Melbourne Radio Australia in English 0500 GMT 
16 Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> BK1603091894 </F>
<F P=104>  Melbourne Radio Australia </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Australia's annual economic growth rate is now 
stated at 4 percent, following the release of figures showing 
growth increase by 1.7 percent in the three months to last 
December. The figures confirmed that an economic recovery is 
underway in Australia. But economists say they are also likely 
to fuel renewed market speculation about an interest rate rise, 
despite comments by the prime minister, Paul Keating, last 
weekend that it was not the time for a rise. 
  The latest increase in growth is broadly based, with the 
official Australian Bureau of Statistics figures showing 
strengths in the housing sector, farming, retail spending, and 
manufacturing. The figures reflect a winding back of government 
spending as the recession eased, the slack being taken up in the 
private sector. However, growth in total business investment 
remained weak. Exports grew during the quarter by 2.2 percent, 
while imports were up by 1.3 percent. 

</TEXT>

