<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reaction to U.S. Trade Representative's Remarks </TI></H3>
<H4>   AMA Head Reacts `Strongly' </H4>
<F P=102> OW1703114794 Tokyo KYODO in English 1112 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1703114794 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 17 KYODO -- A Japanese auto industry 
leader Thursday [17 March] reacted strongly to a remark by U.S. 
Trade Representative Mickey Kantor in which he sought government 
guarantees of Japanese automakers' plans to expand purchases of 
U.S. auto parts. 
  Yutaka Kume, head of the Japan Automobile Manufacturers 
Association [AMA], told reporters that Kantor's comment, made 
earlier in the week, would dampen Japanese carmakers' efforts to 
help put Japan's trade ties with the United States back on a 
normal footing. Referring to a remark by International Trade 
and Industry Minister Hiroshi Kumagai calling on Japanese 
automakers to quickly make public their auto parts purchase 
plans, Kume said it is an individual corporate problem and not a 
government issue. 
  Kume, who is also president of Nissan Motor Co., Japan's No. 
2 automaker, said the government should not comment on 
carmakers' plans, as this tends to cause misunderstanding. 

</TEXT>

