<F P=100> South Korea </F>
<H3> <TI>   IAEA: DPRK Nuclear Inspection `Unsatisfactory' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1703001494 Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network in Korean 2317 GMT 16 
Mar 94 </F>

<F P=103> SK1703001494 </F>
<F P=104>  Seoul KBS-1 Radio Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Korean </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Following inspection of North Korea, the 
International Atomic Energy Agency [IAEA] has concluded that it 
cannot exclude the possibility of additional plutonium 
production in North Korea and has decided to work out sanction 
measures against North Korea by convening a special Board of 
Governors meeting on 21 March. 
  Correspondent Cha Man-sun reports from Vienna: 
  [Begin Cha recording] The IAEA has concluded that the recent 
inspection of North Korea is unsatisfactory [manjok suropchi 
motada]. 
  In an unofficial Board of Governors meeting urgently 
convened 
yesterday [16 March], Director-General Hans Blix revealed that 
North Korea refused to allow the inspection team to conduct 
various activities, including the extraction of sample materials 
from the radiochemical laboratory which is a core target of the 
current inspection. Thus, the IAEA director-general said that 
the IAEA could not examine whether or not nuclear material was 
diverted for other purposes and that the possibility of 
additional plutonium production in North Korea cannot be 
excluded. 
  During this inspection, North Korea refused any extraction 
by 
the the inspection team of sample material from the plutonium 
refining facility. In addition, it refused to allow inspection 
activities surveying (the ?uniformity) of radioactivity in many 
parts of the radiochemical laboratory. Therefore, the suspicion 
of additional plutonium production by North Korea has been 
raised. 
  The IAEA concluded that North Korea's breaking of the 
agreement it previously made by refusing inspections of its core 
facilities is a serious situation. Thus, the IAEA decided to 
convene a special Board of Governors meeting on 21 March with 
the consent of member states of the Board of Governors. 
  At the special Board of Governors meeting on 21 March, the 
IAEA will urge North Korea to sincerely fulfill the nuclear 
accords, will adopt a resolution on sanctions against North 
Korea, and will report the inspection result to the UN Security 
Council. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

