<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reaction to U.S. Trade Representative's Remarks </TI></H3>
<H4>   More Commentary on Kantor Remark </H4>
<F P=102> OW1703041494 Tokyo KYODO in English 0341 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1703041494 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 17 KYODO -- The Japanese Government 
cannot guarantee any market-opening measures to be announced by 
Japan's auto industry regarding imports of auto parts, a 
government source said Thursday. "It's impossible to do what is 
impossible even if U.S. Trade Representative (Mickey) Kantor 
cries out," the source said. 
  Kantor, speaking before the House Trade Subcommittee on 
Tuesday, pointed to a need for government guarantees to ensure 
that the planned steps by the auto industry are effective in 
boosting purchases of U.S. auto parts. 
  Japanese trade officials dismissed Kantor's remark, saying 
the government cannot control business activities as doing so 
runs counter to the government policy of deregulation. 

</TEXT>

