<F P=100> NORTHEAST ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Tokyo Wants U.S. Talks on Multimedia Issue </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1703085394 Tokyo KYODO in English 0824 GMT 17 Mar 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1703085394 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, March 17 KYODO -- Japan wants to discuss 
with the United States legal systems for the advanced 
telecommunication tool called multimedia in the next bilateral 
talks to head off future trade friction in the area, government 
officials said Thursday [17 March]. 
  The officials of the Posts and Telecommunications Ministry 
said the next regular telecommunication talks between the 
ministry and the U.S. Federal Communications Commission are 
slated in Tokyo this summer. They said, under the current legal 
systems in Japan, such services as telephones are regulated by 
telecommunication law, while services like cable television are 
controlled by broadcasting law. Legally, an organization can 
operate in both fields. 
  Providing multimedia services -- a combination of both 
telecommunications and broadcasting -- is therefore allowed to 
any company except for organizations like Nippon Telegraph and 
Telephone Corp. (NTT), KDD [Kokusai Denshin Denwa] and Japan 
Broadcasting Corp. (NHK). Yet, the officials said, new 
regulations have to be considered in actual multimedia services, 
including ways to control privacy. 
  Meanwhile, the U.S. Government, pushing for an advanced 
communication technology called information superhighway, is 
apparently considering changing laws which now prohibit 
organizations to operate in both telecommunication and 
broadcasting fields, the officials said. Japan therefore wants 
to suggest that this issue be taken up in the next talks so the 
two nations can adjust respective legal systems regarding the 
advanced telecommunication field, they said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

