<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Reasons for Ozawa's Canceling U.S. Visit Viewed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  OW1603135694 Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN in Japanese 16 Mar 93 
Morning Edition p 2 -- FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1603135694 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo YOMIURI SHIMBUN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Japanese </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed article: "Ozawa Calls Off His Planned Visit to </F>
Washington To Avert Friction With Takemura"] 
  [Text] On 15 March, Ichiro Ozawa, secretary general of 
Shinseito [Japan Renewal Party], called off his planned visit to 
the United States scheduled for early next week. In the evening 
of 15 March, Mr. Ozawa appeared in the Diet building for the 
first time since 1 March. Answering questions by reporters, he 
said, "I am not prepared for a visit to the United States, and 
it would be impossible for me to visit that country during this 
month." It is believed he called off the planned visit because 
the United States pinned excessively high hopes on his visit to 
Washington because he is a powerful politician in the ruling 
coalition. The objective of Mr. Ozawa's visit to the United 
States, as seen by many, was to break the impasse in the 
Japan-U.S. economic framework talks that remain deadlocked since 
the recent Japan-U.S. summit talks broke down. Mr. Ozawa's 
decision to call off his planned visit is now fueling 
speculation in many quarters. 
  The "National Press Club" organized by the American news 
media had invited Mr. Ozawa to give a lecture, and the 
invitation prompted him to think of visiting the United States. 
Explaining the reasons for Mr. Ozawa calling off his planned 
visit, people close to him stressed he did not plan to visit 
Washington only in connection with the Japan-U.S. framework 
talks. However, a senior member of Shinseito, explaining the 
reason why he canceled his visit to the United States, said: 
"The United States was increasingly pinning high hopes on his 
visit to Washington, saying, since Mr. Ozawa comes to our 
nation, he will carry a bag packed with a lot of gifts. These 
high hopes on the part of the United States made it difficult 
for Mr. Ozawa to go ahead with his planned visit." Some 
American officials took the view that "Mr. Ozawa will visit 
Washington to apologize for breaking off the recent Japan-U.S. 
summit talks" and this view was taken as a factor in his 
cancellation of the visit. 
  Mr. Ozawa himself is said to have vigorously worked on the 
domestic coordination of views in a bid to put the Japan-U.S. 
economic framework talks back on track, and the general 
consensus is that "he aimed to break the deadlock in the 
Japan-U.S. framework talks by visiting the United States." 
However, many point out: Given the character of the Japan-U.S. 
economic framework talks, there are many government ministries 
and agencies involved so it is not easy to break the deadlock. 
The attitude of the United States, that has demanded setting 
numerical targets, is still tough with Japan. Even if Mr. Ozawa 
went ahead with his planned visit to Washington, it would be 
very difficult for him to find areas of agreement for concluding 
the framework talks. 
  Meanwhile, Chief Cabinet Secretary Takemura has been working 
on the domestic coordination of views on how to resume the 
framework talks while calling administrative vice ministers of 
concerned ministries and agencies into the prime minister's 
official residence. Some officials in the government and ruling 
coalition parties take the view that "Mr. Ozawa might have 
decided to call off his planned visit to Washington to avert 
friction with Mr. Takemura." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

