<H5>  Cabinet Support Rate Remains Unchanged </H5>
  The support rate for the Hosokawa cabinet remained almost 
unchanged from the previous survey. However, we should mention 
that two big political events took place during the last month. 
First, the enactment of the political reform bills was 
determined at the 28 January talks between Prime Minister 
Hosokawa and LDP President Kono even though that was thought 
impossible after rejection by the upper house. Most of the 
public welcomed the enactment while it did not believe the bills 
can completely clean up Japan's politics. Second, Prime 
Minister Hosokawa suddenly announced his plan to introduce the 
public welfare tax at a news conference held early in the 
morning of 3 February. The SDPJ opposed this idea at the risk 
of its own survival in the coalition, and the mass media also 
blamed the Hosokawa decision made "without adequate explanation 
to the public." In some opinion polls conducted immediately 
after the announcement, the support rate for Prime Minister 
Hosokawa dropped by nearly 20 percent. In our survey, however, 
the support rate remained unchanged since Prime Minister 
Hosokawa immediately apologized to the public dropping his tax 
increase proposal. Figures in the survey on public satisfaction 
with politics also remained almost unchanged. 


